## How Human Activities Enhance the Greenhouse Effect

Since the Industrial Revolution (~1750), human activities have significantly increased the concentrations of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, intensifying the natural greenhouse effect and causing global warming.

### Sources of Increased Greenhouse Gases

- **Fossil fuel combustion:** Burning coal, oil, and natural gas for electricity, transportation, and industry releases large amounts of CO₂.
- **Deforestation:** Reduces the number of trees available to absorb CO₂ through photosynthesis, increasing atmospheric CO₂ levels.
- **Agriculture:** Produces methane from livestock digestion and rice paddies, and nitrous oxide from fertilizer use.
- **Industrial processes:** Release various greenhouse gases, including chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs).

The atmospheric CO₂ concentration has risen from about 280 parts per million (ppm) pre-industrial to approximately 417 ppm in recent years, a 48% increase ([IPCC AR6](https://www.ipcc.ch/report/ar6/wg1/)). Methane and nitrous oxide levels have also increased significantly beyond natural ranges observed in ice core records spanning hundreds of thousands of years.

### Mechanism of Enhanced Greenhouse Effect

Higher concentrations of greenhouse gases trap more outgoing infrared radiation, reducing the rate at which Earth loses heat to space. This energy imbalance leads to a rise in global surface and atmospheric temperatures, known as global warming.

