## Quantifying Global Warming and Climate Sensitivity

### Equilibrium Climate Sensitivity (ECS)

ECS is defined as the global average surface temperature increase following a doubling of atmospheric CO₂ concentration relative to pre-industrial levels. The latest IPCC report narrows the likely range of ECS to 2.5-4.0°C, with a best estimate of 3.0°C, indicating a stronger warming response than previously thought ([IPCC AR6](https://www.ipcc.ch/report/ar6/wg1/)).

### Transient Climate Response (TCR)

TCR measures the temperature increase at the time CO₂ doubles, assuming a 1% annual increase. The AR6 estimates TCR as 1.4-2.2°C, with a best estimate of 1.8°C.

### Radiative Forcing

Radiative forcing quantifies the change in energy balance due to factors such as greenhouse gases, aerosols, and solar variability. Positive forcing leads to warming, while negative forcing causes cooling. CO₂ has the largest positive radiative forcing among anthropogenic factors, followed by methane and nitrous oxide.

